I love Debbie from Repo Man

While she’s unspeakably beautiful
column182: she has very few (if any at all) specifically feminine qualities in her behaviour. Sure
column183: Otto until the end sees her as a rather passive sex object (starting with his first onscreen attempt to have sex with her and ending with his offer to make her a repo wife)
column184: and Duke talks to her about settling down and getting a baby
column185: but she does nothing to prove them right. At the same time she’s aggressive
column189: as indifferent towards morality and emotions as most of the characters (neither more sensitive and sensible nor horribly and shockingly amoral compared to everyone else)
column191: unlike many female characters in movies who use their sexuality as a means to get something or as a way of interacting with the male characters
column192:
is sexy and has sex simply because she likes it and when she likes it.

\n

Well
column194: I love all the women in Repo Man. Just like with Debbie
column195: there’s nothing specifically woman-y about Marlene or Agent Rogersz except the way they look
column197: even though her part is more gender specific
column198:
is quite fun to watch.

\n

column19: and # comment = some picture I thought I made a funny comment on\nI'm Girlyouwant
column20: a tragically hip girl in a boy's body. I'm not a sissy or a cuckold
column21: I'm not worthless without a dick in my mouth
column22: and I'm ok with trying to be a trans girl and working it out as I go.\nI started this blog almost 4 years ago
column23: basically to post photos of girls I wanted to be. I also post art
column24: and the occasional commentary.\nThere are over 3.5 years and 30

Where your gag comes from.
\n

(TW: sexualized racism + misogyny
column191: for some people (usually white in my experience)
column192: it’s difficult for them to comprehend the perspective that BDSM kink culture is neck-deep in racism and misogyny
column193: particularly in the sexualization of racist-misogynistic historical practices. It’s become quite clear to me over months of pointing out the eerie similarities between the master/slave dynamic that’s common place in bondage subculture and the master/slave dynamic that was quite vividly practiced through patriarchal gender roles between men and women
column194:
as well as slavery…that many people struggle with being able to draw parallels between the techniques of torture slaves were subjected to and the methods of punishment “subs” are subjected to in kink culture. From the whipping to the gags.

\n

It’s been communicated to me
column195: based on the hesitant and confused reception of this argument
column196: that I’m going to need to get visual. This post will include illustrations and imagery that may be potentially disturbing to some viewers
column197: as well as triggering to people who feel mentally disarmed by images of black slavery and female oppression. This will not be my final post on the topic
column198: but it will be an introduction to much larger
column199: much more elaborate posts addressing the racist-patriarchal narratives usually replicated in kink culture (this does not exclude femdom kink practices
column200:
which I’ll be writing about in future posts).

I’ll first like to point out the gag. A torture device used to stop
column202:
with punishments for Intoxication and dirt-eating.”

Torture Devices With A Misogynistic History

External image


 A scold was defined as: “A troublesome and angry woman who by brawling and wrangling amongst her neighbours breaks the public peace
column235: increases discord and becomes a public nuisance to the neighbourhood.” The device was a locking iron muzzle
column236:
metal mask or cage which encased the head. There was an iron curb projecting into the mouth which rested on the top of the tongue. This device prevented the shrew from speaking. In some instances the iron curb was studded with spikes which inflicted pain if the victim spoke. Some branks had a bell built in which drew attention to the scold as she walked through the streets. The woman would be humiliated by the jeering and comments from other people.

THE SCOLD’S BRIDLE

External image
External image
[Scold’s Bridle: This was a metal frame place over a woman’s head. It had a bit that stuck in her mouth to prevent her talking. The scold’s bridle or branks was used in Scotland by the 16th century and was used in England from the 17th century. It was last used in Britain in 1824].

Made by blacksmiths
column237: the bridle was a cage-like device
column238: made from iron. It was approximately nine inches high and seven inches wide
column239: and was fitted to the woman’s head. The most basic type was made of a band of iron
column240: which was hinged at the side and had a protruding part
column242: that could be flat or with a spike
column243: which went into the woman’s mouth
column244: to hold her tongue down. Another band of iron went over her head
column245: the front of which was shaped for her nose to go through. Depending on the design
column248: and scarring of the tongue was not uncommon. Some had a bell secured to a spring
column249: which was attached to the bridle
column250:
so the wearer could be heard as she approached.

External image

Some houses had a hook in the wall at the side of the fireplace where the wife would be chained
column251: until she promised to behave herself and curb her tongue. Although sometimes fitted to a nagging wife by the local gaoler (jailer) at the request of her husband
column253: it was more often a punitive sentence ordered by a magistrate. Judicial bridles were more elaborate than the basic type; they always had at least one spike and they could be locked. They also had a chain attached to the side of the bridle
column254: with a ring on the end. This could be used to publicly humiliate the woman by leading her through the town
column255: or staking her at a designated area for a set time period. The amount of time the bridle was worn could be from 30 minutes to several hours
column256: depending on the seriousness of the offense
column257:
during which time the miscreant would not be able to eat or drink. It was also said to be used on witches to prevent them from chanting or casting spells.

It’s pretty evident that when some women
column259: argue that BDSM kink culture has an overwhelming amount of racist-misogyny embedded in its practice of reenacting  bondage and inequitable dynamics
column260: they have a reasonable argument worth considering. It’s not difficult to understand the viewpoint that some kinks take things steeped in the actual subordination and oppression of people and turn it into a sexualized drama that’s just “fun and games
column261:
” for the (hopefully consensual) participants involved.

\n

If you are engaged in kinky
column263: your gut-reaction is most likely to defend something you’ve learnt to enjoy despite its highly problematic elements. However
column264: the primary intent of this post isn’t to persuade you to stop practicing these things
column265:
but to come to realize that kink culture is still affected by whiteness and patriarchy while relying on it all the same. Relying on the use of sometimes and somewhat altered methods of torture to be able to act out scenes that induce discomfort and/or pain and to keep within the narrative of unequal power relations and acted abuse.

Basket.js: A JavaScript Loader With LocalStorage-based Script Caching

Basket.js is an interesting project that caches JavaScript files in localStorage for subsequent requests rather than relying on the browser’s built-in caching features.  I’ve long thought about doing something like this using the FileSystem API
column182:
but localStorage is probably a better idea (at least for fallback) since it is supported everywhere (even IE8).

\n

External image

\n

Why do this and not just use the browser’s cache?  Because it’s faster
column183: according to tests performed by both Google and Bing
column184:
both of which employ the technique on their sites now.  Basket.js enables you to take advantage of the same technique in your sites and apps.

\n

It works by first loading a small stub file (Basket.js itself) and then checking to see whether your other scripts are already cached in localStorage
column185: and if not or if they are expired
column186: loading them via XHR and caching for subsequent loads.  Basket.js has a nice Promise-based API
column187:
using RSVP.js which allows you to require scripts and inject them into the page to execute.

\n

It’s a fairly simple project
column188: but implements a very useful idea.  I’d love to see a FileSystem API based version as well to see how performance varies compared to localStorage.  Apparently they’ve already tried IndexedDB and found it to be much slower than localStorage
column189: which I found surprising.  In either case
column190: both the FileSystem API and IndexedDB are designed more for this use-case
column191: and have much larger quotas than localStorage
column192:
so it would be useful to experiment with them both in the future.

\n

It would also be interesting to combine this with the App Cache API to provide offline support.  App Cache has a lot of problems
column193: so if you could get it down so that it only had to store a small HTML stub file containing a small amount of JavaScript to load everything else from the FileSystem API
column195: your app would work both offline and online
column196: without most of the headache of App Cache.  As long as the HTML stub file never needed to change
column197: your JavaScript would be in full control of when and how things are loaded and cached.  It’s an interesting idea
column198:
and one I think would be fun to explore.

\n

Anyway
column199:
I thought Basket.js was worth a mention.  You can check out the source on Github.

\n

MathBox.js: A 3d Math Visualization Library using WebGL

I’ve always been impressed by the work of Steven Wittens
column182: and MathBox.js is certainly no exception.  MathBox.js is a JavaScript library for creating high quality 3d math visualizations using WebGL.  It is built on top of Three.js and tQuery
column183: which is a jQuery-like API for Three.js.  MathBox.js provides APIs to “visualize mathematical relationships and animate them smoothly”.  MathBox has a nice jQuery-like API as well
column184: with chained methods for defining how visualizations appear and animate
column185:
as well as the actual mathematical functions themselves.

\n

\n

MathBox.js starts with a library of WebGL shaders that must be loaded.  It makes use of another library called ShaderGraph.js
column186: which takes the source code for multiple shaders
column188:
and combines them together into a single output shader.  This enables you to have shader components that can be reused in various configurations.

\n

Once everything is loaded
column189: it’s your job as a user of the library to define what you want to be displayed.  As mentioned above
column190: you do this using a variety of library methods to define the viewport
column192: and objects that appear in a scene such as axes
column196:
and surfaces.  You can even enable user interaction to rotate the camera using your mouse.

\n

\n

There are a variety of demos available for you to check out
column197: and more linked to from the Github page.  Make sure to view them in a WebGL compatible browser (anything but IE and Safari unless you’ve enabled it these days).  As you can see
column198: the rendering and animation is super smooth
column200:
it seems incredibly simple to use given the output you get.

\n

There is an excellent article about the inspiration and process behind MathBox including a video of a talk from the Full Frontal conference that you should check out
column201: as well as the code on Github.  It’s exciting to see WebGL taking shape and enabling functionality on the web previously reserved for native applications.  If you ever need to render high quality 3d math visualizations on the web
column202:
MathBox.js seems to be the place to go!

\n

Stock Prediction

The Stock Prediction Challenge was one of the vaguer challenges in the hackathon. Instead of having a set problem to solve
column174: you needed to buy and sell stocks and try to earn the most money. While approximate challenges often involve trying out different approaches
column176: since the future stock prices were unknown. However
column177:
a sample stock file was provided with the challenge that contained similar patterns to what was used in the actual contest. You could analyze this data (or use a program to analyze it) to detect the stock movement patterns. You could then write the actual program that would look for those patterns to buy and sell stocks.

\n

Alexander did fairly well on this challenge using a very simple approach. Every day
column178: he sold any stocks that had gone up in price and bought as many stocks as he could that had gone down by the highest percentage. He then worked on improving his approach. He started by selecting and sorting all the stocks that had gone down by at least 4% since the day before. He would then buy as many as possible from the stock that had gone down the most
column179: which would often use up almost all the money. If there was leftover money
column180: he would buy the next-most decreased stock that he could buy
column182: until he used up his money. This simple strategy was enough to turn his $100 into $80
column184:
and earned him 17th place on the back-to-school leaderboard. You can view Alexander’s code on Github.

\n

The higher-ranking contestants were able to earn even more money by finding  more patterns in the data. While stocks often went up after going down and vice versa
column185: this was not always true. Certain stocks fluctuated more
column186: so it was worth buying more of those stocks when they went down then the less volatile stocks. Sometimes it might have been worth saving money from one turn to the next so you could buy a large number of cheap stocks. There was also another hidden pattern – certain stocks followed other stocks movements 30 days apart. If you realized such a pattern might exist
column187: you could have stored the stock data from the previous 30 days
column188: and then analyzed it to find out which stocks were following the movements of other stocks. This pattern was stronger than the simple up-and-down pattern
column189: so you could have made more money by following it when possible. By using a more sophisticated analysis
column190:
you could have earned millions of dollars trading!

\n

This challenge was somewhat “fuzzy” so it’s a bit more like the messy world than the clear-cut logic of some programming challenges. We may have more challenges like this in the future
column191: perhaps with less clear-cut patterns. With enough of these challenges
column192:
people will soon be able to write their own algorithms to do real trading! (Note: Similar results are not guaranteed!)

\n

TraceGL: A JavaScript Codeflow Visualization and Debugging Tool using WebGL

\n

Rik Arends has just released TraceGL
column182: an interesting JavaScript codeflow debugging tool using WebGL for its UI rendering.  Described as “an oscilloscope
column184: TraceGL is an improvement on the familiar step debuggers that can be found in browser dev tools like Chrome
column186:
and now Firefox itself.

\n

TraceGL works by instrumenting all of your code so it knows when calls took place
column187: and all of the boolean logic that determined which code path to take.  Then it visualizes all of this
column189: showing you a high level overview called the “mini map” in the top left
column190: a log of function calls in the top right
column191: the call stack in the bottom left
column192:
and finally the code for the function in the bottom right.

\n

As your code runs
column193: TraceGL visualizes all of this data in real time.  The mini map is useful to see the ebbs and flows of the code
column194: i.e. where the stack gets deeper and shallower again.  In this way
column195: you can see where events are being processed
column196: like mouse or keyboard events in the browser
column197: or HTTP requests in a Node.js application
column198: and then get to a section of the potentially very long call stack very quickly.  TraceGL even works over asynchronous events
column200: which means that these operations are still shown as part of a single call stack under their originating calls
column201:
rather than as separate events.

Here is a video showing TraceGL in use:

TraceGL can instrument both browser based and Node.js applications
column202: and integrates with various editors so that double clicking a line can open your favorite editor.  An interesting aspect of the UI is that it is written entirely using WebGL
column204: all of the text rendering (most of the UI) must have been done in a 2d canvas and then uploaded to WebGL as a texture since WebGL has no native text rendering capabilities
column205: but clever rendering tricks like only re-rendering what has changed can make things fast.  And once the textures are on the GPU
column208:
etc. using shaders is very fast.

\n

I think we’re probably going to see more and more WebGL user interfaces soon.  We’ve seen a lot of 3D stuff written on top of WebGL
column209: and it is certainly good for that
column210: but I’m betting that normal 2D user interfaces on the web will start being written with it too
column211: just thanks to its great performance characteristics.  HTML and CSS is great for documents and applications
column213: but for web apps to compete with native on performance
column214:
hardware accelerated UIs on top of WebGL will be important.

\n

Of course
column215: building user interfaces using WebGL means that any text rendering that is done won’t be selectable
column217: or accessible to screen readers without lots of additional work
column218: so I can see frameworks being developed to facilitate this.  I’ve already been working on and off on something similar to Apple’s Core Animation framework on top of WebGL (not public yet)
column219: and other interesting 2D frameworks like Pixi.js have been released recently.  Especially with WebGL’s likely support in Internet Explorer 11
column220: I think the age of WebGL user interfaces is upon us
column221:
and it’s  exciting!

\n

You can check out TraceGL on their website.  It costs $15 to buy
column222: but not all good tools are free and it’s nice to support good developers
column223:
so give it a shot and let me know what you think in the comments!

\n

"title_font_weight":"bold"}}" data-peepr="{"tumblelog":"hautepop"}">hautepop
Positive Mental Attitude

A thing that’s struck me this year: the compulsory “positive mental attitude” requirement of digital media and technology conferences.

Everything is great
column192: and “revolutionary” (but without the deaths or the state violence)
column193:
and every challenge is an “opportunity”.

\n\n

A website doing nothing new technologically is always “innovative” nonetheless
column194: and presents a mission statement in terms of changing the world
column195:
not just selling more vintage knick-knacks or plane tickets.

It’s kind of infuriating because there’s no critical awareness.

It’s ok to reproduce psuedo-facts and cliches
column196:
and these seem to pass for “big ideas”.

But maybe I am thinking about this wrong.

I mean
column198: the intellectual standards are pretty shit. But the requirement for big ideas - or at least to seek them
column199:
to attempt them - might be a good thing.

It’s about finding solutions.

Making things.

Look at what all these terrifying “Top under-30s” do. They create stuff:

And this is what I’m missing in my thinking.

I can find all sorts of problems
column200:
but don’t suggest much of a way forward.

Because that’s a harder problem to solve.

Now that social networking has become universal
column220: we’ve become increasingly sensitive to what we share on Facebook. Speaking on a stage in front of a mixed audience of family
column222: and acquaintances makes it hard for most of us to be our genuine and authentic selves. As a result
column223: we tend to see people sharing only their proudest moments in an attempt to portray their best selves. We filter too much
column225:
we lose real human connection.
—  http://takeaswig.com/the-end-of-the-facebook-era

Rabid fans clamored to throw their support and money at the project. They crowded around booths at trade shows to catch a glimpse
column220: and built complicated software programs for the new platform– sometimes without even being able to try it out themselves. Suddenly
column221: users were booting up and creating any virtual world they wanted
column222:
and that power made them think they might be able to influence the real world a bit. Hopes were high! Oculus seemed untouchable; the white knight of VR.

\n\n

Well
column223:
fuck it. Facebook just bought the thing.

—  Oculus was the future of gaming. Now it’s the future of Facebook. one of sadder articles about Facebooks latest acquisition.

Feelings of Failure
column183:
Foster Aggression in Video Gamers

\n

The disturbing imagery or violent storylines of videos games like World of Warcraft or Grand Theft Auto are often accused of fostering feelings of aggression in players. But a new study shows hostile behavior is linked to gamers’ experiences of failure and frustration during play—not to a game’s violent content.

\n

The study is the first to look at the player’s psychological experience with video games instead of focusing solely on its content. Researchers found that failure to master a game and its controls led to frustration and aggression
column184:
regardless of whether the game was violent or not. The findings of the study were published online in the March edition of the Journal of Personality and Social Psychology.

\n

“Any player who has thrown down a remote control after losing an electronic game can relate to the intense feelings or anger failure can cause
column186: a researcher at the Oxford Internet Institute at Oxford University
column187:
who said such frustration is commonly known among gamers as “rage-quitting.”

\n
